[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cut** is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] Any cut determines a **cut-set**, the set of edges that have one endpoint in each subset of the partition.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] These edges are said to **cross** the cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] In a connected graph, each cut-set determines a unique cut, and in some cases cuts are identified with their cut-sets rather than with their vertex partitions.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] In a flow network, an **s–t cut** is a cut that requires the *source* and the *sink* to be in different subsets, and its *cut-set* only consists of edges going from the source's side to the sink's side.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The *capacity* of an s–t cut is defined as the sum of the capacity of each edge in the *cut-set*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] A **cut** *C* = (*S*, *T*) is a partition of V of a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) into two subsets S and T.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The **cut-set** of a cut *C* = (*S*, *T*) is the set {(*u*, *v*) ∈ *E* | *u* ∈ *S*, *v* ∈ *T*} of edges that have one endpoint in S and the other endpoint in T.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] If s and t are specified vertices of the graph G, then an **s–t cut** is a cut in which s belongs to the set S and t belongs to the set T.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] In an unweighted undirected graph, the *size* or *weight* of a cut is the number of edges crossing the cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] In a weighted graph, the **value** or **weight** is defined by the sum of the weights of the edges crossing the cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] A **bond** is a cut-set that does not have any other cut-set as a proper subset.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *minimum* if the size or weight of the cut is not larger than the size of any other cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a minimum cut: the size of this cut is 2, and there is no cut of size 1 because the graph is bridgeless.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow min-cut theorem proves that the maximum network flow and the sum of the cut-edge weights of any minimum cut that separates the source and the sink are equal.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] There are polynomial-time methods to solve the min-cut problem, notably the Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *maximum* if the size of the cut is not smaller than the size of any other cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a maximum cut: the size of the cut is equal to 5, and there is no cut of size 6, or |*E*| (the number of edges), because the graph is not bipartite (there is an odd cycle).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] In general, finding a maximum cut is computationally hard.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is also APX-hard, meaning that there is no polynomial-time approximation scheme for it unless P = NP.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] However, it can be approximated to within a constant approximation ratio using semidefinite programming.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] Note that min-cut and max-cut are *not* dual problems in the linear programming sense, even though one gets from one problem to other by changing min to max in the objective function.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow problem is the dual of the min-cut problem.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The **sparsest cut problem** is to bipartition the vertices so as to minimize the ratio of the number of edges across the cut divided by the number of vertices in the smaller half of the partition.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] This objective function favors solutions that are both sparse (few edges crossing the cut) and balanced (close to a bisection).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The problem is known to be NP-hard, and the best known approximation algorithm is an $O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ approximation due to Arora, Rao & Vazirani (2009).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] The family of all cut sets of an undirected graph is known as the **cut space** of the graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] It forms a vector space over the two-element finite field of arithmetic modulo two, with the symmetric difference of two cut sets as the vector addition operation, and is the orthogonal complement of the cycle space.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] If the edges of the graph are given positive weights, the minimum weight basis of the cut space can be described by a tree on the same vertex set as the graph, called the Gomory–Hu tree.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/cut-graph-theory] Each edge of this tree is associated with a bond in the original graph, and the minimum cut between two nodes *s* and *t* is the minimum weight bond among the ones associated with the path from *s* to *t* in the tree.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] In graph theory, an **edge contraction** is an operation that removes an edge from a graph while simultaneously merging the two vertices that it previously joined.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Edge contraction is a fundamental operation in the theory of graph minors.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] **Vertex identification** is a less restrictive form of this operation.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] The **edge contraction** operation occurs relative to a particular edge, e .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] The edge e is removed and its two incident vertices, u and v , are merged into a new vertex w , where the edges incident to w each correspond to an edge incident to either u or v .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] More generally, the operation may be performed on a set of edges by contracting each edge (in any order).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] The resulting graph is sometimes written as $G/e$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] As defined below, an edge contraction operation may result in a graph with multiple edges even if the original graph was a simple graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] However, some authors disallow the creation of multiple edges, so that edge contractions performed on simple graphs always produce simple graphs.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Let $G=(V,E)$ be a graph (*or directed graph*) containing an edge $e=(u,v)$ with $u\neq v$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Let f be a function that maps every vertex in $V\setminus \{u,v\}$ to itself, and otherwise, maps it to a new vertex w .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] The contraction of e results in a new graph $G'=(V',E')$ , where $V'=(V\setminus \{u,v\})\cup \{w\}$ , $E'=E\setminus \{e\}$ , and for every $x\in V$ , $x'=f(x)\in V'$ is incident to an edge $e'\in E'$ if and only if, the corresponding edge, $e\in E$ is incident to x in G .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Suppose we can obtain the graph G by identifying the vertices $u_{1}$ of $G_{1}$ and $u_{2}$ of $G_{2}$ as the vertex u of G and identifying the vertices $v_{1}$ of $G_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ of $G_{2}$ as the vertex v of G .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Given a finite set of edges, the order in which contractions are performed on a graph does not change the result (up to isomorphism).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] The result reduces to showing that $G/e/(f/e)$ is isomorphic to $G/f/(e/f)$ for two edges $e,f$ of G .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Both edge and vertex contraction techniques are valuable in proof by induction on the number of vertices or edges in a graph, where it can be assumed that a property holds for all smaller graphs and this can be used to prove the property for the larger graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Edge contraction is used in the recursive formula for the number of spanning trees of an arbitrary connected graph, and in the recurrence formula for the chromatic polynomial of a simple graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Contractions are also useful in structures where we wish to simplify a graph by identifying vertices that represent essentially equivalent entities.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] One of the most common examples is the reduction of a general directed graph to an acyclic directed graph by contracting all of the vertices in each strongly connected component.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] If the relation described by the graph is transitive, no information is lost as long as we label each vertex with the set of labels of the vertices that were contracted to form it.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Another example is the coalescing performed in global graph coloring register allocation, where vertices are contracted (where it is safe) in order to eliminate move operations between distinct variables.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/edge-contraction] Edge contraction is used in 3D modelling packages (either manually, or through some feature of the modelling software) to consistently reduce vertex count, aiding in the creation of low-polygon models.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] In computer science and graph theory, **Karger's algorithm** is a randomized algorithm to compute a minimum cut of a connected graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] It was invented by David Karger and first published in 1993.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The idea of the algorithm is based on the concept of contraction of an edge $(u,v)$ in an undirected graph $G=(V,E)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Informally, the contraction of an edge merges the nodes u and v into one, reducing the total number of nodes of the graph by one.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] All other edges connecting either u or v are "reattached" to the merged node, effectively producing a multigraph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Karger's basic algorithm iteratively contracts randomly chosen edges until only two nodes remain; those nodes represent a cut in the original graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] By iterating this basic algorithm a sufficient number of times, a minimum cut can be found with high probability.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] A *cut* $(S,T)$ in an undirected graph $G=(V,E)$ is a partition of the vertices V into two non-empty, disjoint sets $S\cup T=V$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The *cutset* of a cut consists of the edges $\{\,uv\in E\colon u\in S,v\in T\,\}$ between the two parts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] There are $2^{|V|}$ ways of choosing for each vertex whether it belongs to S or to T , but two of these choices make S or T empty and do not give rise to cuts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Among the remaining choices, swapping the roles of S and T does not change the cut, so each cut is counted twice; therefore, there are $2^{|V|-1}-1$ distinct cuts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The *minimum cut problem* is to find a cut of smallest size among these cuts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] which agrees with the unweighted definition for $w=1$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] A cut is sometimes called a “global cut” to distinguish it from an “ s - t cut” for a given pair of vertices, which has the additional requirement that $s\in S$ and $t\in T$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Every global cut is an s - t cut for some $s,t\in V$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Better deterministic algorithms for the global minimum cut problem include the Stoer–Wagner algorithm, which has a running time of $O(mn+n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The fundamental operation of Karger’s algorithm is a form of edge contraction.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The result of contracting the edge $e=\{u,v\}$ is a new node $uv$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Every edge $\{w,u\}$ or $\{w,v\}$ for $w\notin \{u,v\}$ to the endpoints of the contracted edge is replaced by an edge $\{w,uv\}$ to the new node.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Finally, the contracted nodes u and v with all their incident edges are removed.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] In particular, the resulting graph contains no self-loops.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The result of contracting edge e is denoted $G/e$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The contraction algorithm repeatedly contracts random edges in the graph, until only two nodes remain, at which point there is only a single cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The key idea of the algorithm is that it is far more likely for non min-cut edges than min-cut edges to be randomly selected and lost to contraction, since min-cut edges are usually vastly outnumbered by non min-cut edges.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Subsequently, it is plausible that the min-cut edges will survive all the edge contraction, and the algorithm will correctly identify the min-cut edge.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] When the graph is represented using adjacency lists or an adjacency matrix, a single edge contraction operation can be implemented with a linear number of updates to the data structure, for a total running time of $O(|V|^{2})$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Alternatively, the procedure can be viewed as an execution of Kruskal’s algorithm for constructing the minimum spanning tree in a graph where the edges have weights $w(e_{i})=\pi (i)$ according to a random permutation $\pi$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Removing the heaviest edge of this tree results in two components that describe a cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] In this way, the contraction procedure can be implemented like Kruskal’s algorithm in time $O(|E|\log |E|)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The best known implementations use $O(|E|)$ time and space, or $O(|E|\log |E|)$ time and $O(|V|)$ space, respectively.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] In a graph $G=(V,E)$ with $n=|V|$ vertices, the contraction algorithm returns a minimum cut with polynomially small probability ${\binom {n}{2}}^{-1}$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Recall that every graph has $2^{n-1}-1$ cuts (by the discussion in the previous section), among which at most ${\tbinom {n}{2}}$ can be minimum cuts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] Therefore, the success probability for this algorithm is much better than the probability for picking a cut at random, which is at most ${\frac {\tbinom {n}{2}}{2^{n-1}-1}}$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] For instance, the cycle graph on n vertices has exactly ${\binom {n}{2}}$ minimum cuts, given by every choice of 2 edges.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The contraction procedure finds each of these with equal probability.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] To further establish the lower bound on the success probability, let C denote the edges of a specific minimum cut of size k .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The contraction algorithm returns C if none of the random edges deleted by the algorithm belongs to the cutset C .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] In particular, the first edge contraction avoids C , which happens with probability $1-k/|E|$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The minimum degree of G is at least k (otherwise a minimum degree vertex would induce a smaller cut where one of the two partitions contains only the minimum degree vertex), so $|E|\geqslant nk/2$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The total running time for T repetitions for a graph with n vertices and m edges is $O(Tm)=O(n^{2}m\log n)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] An extension of Karger’s algorithm due to David Karger and Clifford Stein achieves an order of magnitude improvement.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The basic idea is to perform the contraction procedure until the graph reaches t vertices.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] In particular, the probability that an edge from C is contracted grows towards the end.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] This motivates the idea of switching to a slower algorithm after a certain number of contraction steps.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The contraction parameter t is chosen so that each call to contract has probability at least 1/2 of success (that is, of avoiding the contraction of an edge from a specific cutset C ).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] This allows the successful part of the recursion tree to be modeled as a random binary tree generated by a critical Galton–Watson process, and to be analyzed accordingly.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] To achieve error probability $O(1/n)$ , the algorithm can be repeated $O(\log n/P(n))$ times, for an overall running time of $T(n)\cdot {\frac {\log n}{P(n)}}=O(n^{2}\log ^{3}n)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] This is an order of magnitude improvement over Karger’s original algorithm.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] To determine a min-cut, one has to touch every edge in the graph at least once, which is $\Theta (n^{2})$ time in a dense graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/karger-s-algorithm] The Karger–Stein's min-cut algorithm takes the running time of $O(n^{2}\ln ^{O(1)}n)$ , which is very close to that.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In graph theory, a **minimum cut** or **min-cut** of a graph is a cut (a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets) that is minimal in some metric.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In the simplest *unweighted min-cut problem*, the goal is to minimize the number of edges connecting the two parts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] Variations of the minimum cut problem consider *weighted graphs*, *directed graphs*, *terminals*, and partitioning the vertices into *more than two sets*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] The weighted min-cut problem allowing both positive and negative weights can be trivially transformed into a weighted maximum cut problem by flipping the sign in all weights.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] The required output is a partition V = S + T (a partition of the vertices into two disjoint subsets S and T).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] Any such partition has a *cost,* and the goal is to find a partition with a smallest cost.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] A generalization of the minimum cut problem without terminals is the minimum k-cut, in which the goal is to partition the graph into at least k connected components by removing as few edges as possible.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] For a fixed value of k, this problem can be solved in polynomial time, though the algorithm is not practical for large k.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In the variant called *min s-t cut*, the input contains, in addition to the graph, two nodes called *s* (source) and *t* (target / sink).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] The required output is a partition V = S + T such that s is in S and t is in T.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In a flow network, the minimum cut separates the source and sink vertices and minimizes the total sum of the capacities of the edges that are directed from the source side of the cut to the sink side of the cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] As shown in the max-flow min-cut theorem, the weight of this cut equals the maximum amount of flow that can be sent from the source to the sink in the given network.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In a weighted, undirected network, it is possible to calculate the cut that separates a particular pair of vertices from each other and has minimum possible total cost.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] A system of cuts that solves this problem for every possible vertex pair can be collected into a structure known as the Gomory–Hu tree of the graph.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] A generalization of the minimum cut problem with terminals is the k-terminal cut, or multi-terminal cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In a planar graph, this problem can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] However, in general this problem is NP-hard, even for $k=3$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] Graph partition problems are a family of combinatorial optimization problems in which a graph is to be partitioned into two or more parts with additional constraints such as balancing the sizes of the two sides of the cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] Segmentation-based object categorization can be viewed as a specific case of normalized min-cut spectral clustering applied to image segmentation.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] It can also be used as a generic clustering method, where the nodes are data samples assumed to be taken from a metric space and edge weights are their distances.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] This is however often impractical due do the high computational complexity for $k>2$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] Due to max-flow min-cut theorem, 2 nodes' Minimum cut value is equal to their maxflow value.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] In this case, some algorithms used in maxflow problem could also be used to solve this question.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] A graph with n vertices can at the most have ${\binom {n}{2}}={\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ distinct minimum cuts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/minimum-cut] This bound is tight in the sense that a (simple) cycle on n vertices has exactly ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ minimum cuts.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] In computing, a **Monte Carlo algorithm** is a randomized algorithm whose output may be incorrect with a certain (typically small) probability.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Two examples of such algorithms are the Karger–Stein algorithm and the Monte Carlo algorithm for minimum feedback arc set.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] The name refers to the Monte Carlo casino in the Principality of Monaco, which is well-known around the world as an icon of gambling.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] The term "Monte Carlo" was first introduced in 1947 by Nicholas Metropolis.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms are a dual of Monte Carlo algorithms and never return an incorrect answer.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] However, they may make random choices as part of their work.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] As a result, the time taken might vary between runs, even with the same input.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] If there is a procedure for verifying whether the answer given by a Monte Carlo algorithm is correct, and the probability of a correct answer is bounded above zero, then with probability one, running the algorithm repeatedly while testing the answers will eventually give a correct answer.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Whether this process is a Las Vegas algorithm depends on whether halting with probability one is considered to satisfy the definition.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] While the answer returned by a deterministic algorithm is always expected to be correct, this is not the case for Monte Carlo algorithms.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] For decision problems, these algorithms are generally classified as either **false**-biased or **true**-biased.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] A **false**-biased Monte Carlo algorithm is always correct when it returns **false**; a **true**-biased algorithm is always correct when it returns **true**.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] While this describes algorithms with *one-sided errors*, others might have no bias; these are said to have *two-sided errors*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] The answer they provide (either **true** or **false**) will be incorrect, or correct, with some bounded probability.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] For instance, the Solovay–Strassen primality test is used to determine whether a given number is a prime number.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] It always answers **true** for prime number inputs; for composite inputs, it answers **false** with probability at least 1⁄2 and **true** with probability less than 1⁄2.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Thus, **false** answers from the algorithm are certain to be correct, whereas the **true** answers remain uncertain; this is said to be a *1⁄2-correct false-biased algorithm*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] For a Monte Carlo algorithm with one-sided errors, the failure probability can be reduced (and the success probability amplified) by running the algorithm *k* times.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Consider again the Solovay–Strassen algorithm which is *1⁄2-correct false-biased*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] One may run this algorithm multiple times returning a **false** answer if it reaches a **false** response within *k* iterations, and otherwise returning **true**.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Thus, if the number is prime then the answer is always correct, and if the number is composite then the answer is correct with probability at least 1−(1−1⁄2)*k* = 1−2*−k*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] For Monte Carlo decision algorithms with two-sided error, the failure probability may again be reduced by running the algorithm *k* times and returning the majority function of the answers.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] In contrast, the complexity class ZPP describes problems solvable by polynomial expected time Las Vegas algorithms.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] ZPP ⊆ RP ⊆ BPP, but it is not known whether any of these complexity classes is distinct from each other; that is, Monte Carlo algorithms may have more computational power than Las Vegas algorithms, but this has not been proven.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Another complexity class, PP, describes decision problems with a polynomial-time Monte Carlo algorithm that is more accurate than flipping a coin but where the error probability cannot necessarily be bounded away from 1⁄2.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are primarily divided by its two main types, Monte Carlo and Las Vegas, however, these represent only a top of the hierarchy and can be further categorized.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Previous table represents a general framework for Monte Carlo and Las Vegas randomized algorithms.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Instead of the mathematical symbol < one could use $\leq$ , thus making probabilities in the worst case equal.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/monte-carlo-algorithm] Well-known Monte Carlo algorithms include the Solovay–Strassen primality test, the Baillie–PSW primality test, the Miller–Rabin primality test, and certain fast variants of the Schreier–Sims algorithm in computational group theory.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Recall that the contraction of two nodes, *u* and *v*, in a (multi-)graph yields a new node *u* ' with edges that are the union of the edges incident on either *u* or *v*, except from any edge(s) connecting *u* and *v*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Figure 1 gives an example of contraction of vertex *A* and *B*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] After contraction, the resulting graph may have parallel edges, but contains no self loops.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] In each execution of the outer loop, the algorithm repeats the inner loop until only 2 nodes remain, the corresponding cut is obtained.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The run time of one execution is $O(n)$ , and *n* denotes the number of vertices.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] After *m* times executions of the outer loop, we output the minimum cut among all the results.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The figure 2 gives an example of one execution of the algorithm.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] After execution, we get a cut of size 3.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] If *G* is not connected, then *G* can be partitioned into *L* and *R* without any edge between them.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] So the min cut in a disconnected graph is 0.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Initially, *u*,*v* are distinct vertices.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] *As long as we pick an edge ⁠ $f\neq e$ ⁠, u and v do not get merged.* Thus, at the end of the algorithm, we have two compound nodes covering the entire graph, one consisting of the vertices of *L* and the other consisting of the vertices of *R*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] As in figure 2, the size of min cut is 1, and *C* = {(*A*,*B*)}.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] If we don't select (*A*,*B*) for contraction, we can get the min cut.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Because the min cut is *k*, every vertex *v* must satisfy degree(*v*) ≥ *k*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, the sum of the degree is at least *pk*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] But it is well known that the sum of vertex degrees equals 2|*E*|.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the algorithm succeeds is 1 − the probability that all attempts fail.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] By lemma 1, the probability that *C**i* = *C* is the probability that no edge of *C* is selected during iteration *i*.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Consider the inner loop and let *G**j* denote the graph after *j* edge contractions, where *j* ∈ {0, 1, …, *n* − 3}.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] We use the chain rule of conditional possibilities.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the edge chosen at iteration *j* is not in *C*, given that no edge of *C* has been chosen before, is $1-{\frac {k}{|E(G_{j})|}}$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Note that *G**j* still has min cut of size *k*, so by Lemma 2, it still has at least ${\frac {(n-j)k}{2}}$ edges.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Thus the probability that the algorithm succeeds is at least $1-\left(1-{\frac {2}{n(n-1)}}\right)^{m}$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] The algorithm finds the min cut with probability $1-{\frac {1}{n}}$ , in time $O(mn)=O(n^{3}\log n)$ .
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:karger-randomized-cut/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
